-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> which dominate</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> raw materials </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">trade for </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">food </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">production</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> but cleverly</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> still remain </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">hidden from</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> the European </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">consumer’s</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> radar</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">, potentially due to ignorance</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">surrounding the p</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">roduction </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">of food</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">Known as the ABCD group</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">, ADM, Bunge, Cargill </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">and Louis Dreyfus,</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> account for between 75% and 90% of the global grain trade which is an incredibly influential market</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> affecting</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> not only arable farmers but also diary producers and </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">sustainable fuel suppliers.</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">2</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">Moreover, s</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">even companies control </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">virtually a</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">ll fertiliser supply, f</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">ive companies share 68%of the world’s agrochemical market </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">and t</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">hree companies control almost 50%of the proprietary seeds market</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">3</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 26.76pt; padding-left:5.44pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">While the UK </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> perceived as a relatively small </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">player</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> in agricultural markets, it </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">happily</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> acts as a base for </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">many</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">transnational corporations</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">. Th</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">e strength of transnational companies </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">has</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">resulted in a </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">shift</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">trade </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">power away from </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">governments and</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> supranational bodies towards corporate businesses. </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">With</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> relatively few traders purchasing agricult</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">ural commodities </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">in bulk on the international market, </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">these companies have enormous </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">leverage in setting the purchase price</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">, particularly with large scale producers with whom the</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">y contr</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">act directly with.</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">has been</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> a source of concern for British farmers who are exposed to t</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">ransnational company influence over their ‘grain elevators’ who are the point of contact for British commodity trade. The ABCD companies buy the grain from elevators and then process it into feed</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> for livestock or as feedstock for biofuels. This vertical dominance means that there is little room for price transparency.</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">4</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 26.76pt; padding-left:5.44pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">Even the government have been unnervingly accepting in promoting increase</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">trade</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> as a method of obtaining British </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">food </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">security </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">even though</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">this </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">actively places farmers into the</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> volatile</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> hands of </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">transnational companies</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">lthough the EU is a major player in the world’s wheat import market, the UK in isolation is not ver</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">y powerful. </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">Britain</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> rel</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">ies</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> upon </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">imports to fill the</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> 40%</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> gap </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">commodity </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">demand</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">thus </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">the volatility of the grain market </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">especially</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">poses very serious </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">inflationary price </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">challenges to </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">the UK</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">In 2010, the UK </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">experienced </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> significant wheat price spike in cereal products after Moscow chose to impose a </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">cereal export ban in</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">response </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">to lower domestic yields caused by </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">a damaging </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">heat wave. Due to the value of Russia as a global leader in grain exports, their bad harvest has more of an effect on the British consumers than if there was a failed harvest in Br</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">itain. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><img src="data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAp4AAAACCAYAAADxTdyCAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAAA+SURBVFhH7dbBDQAwCAMxNs/otAwBL0diAeseVP0lacdAAxrQgAY0oAENaGCrgfk5jQABAgQIECBAgMCJwAMiUHvrcf9gLwAAAABJRU5ErkJggg==" width="669" height="1" alt="" style="margin-left:2.85pt; margin-top:7.8pt; position:absolute; z-index:1" /></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:9pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.8pt; padding-left:6.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:9pt">The Guardian, ‘</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">The global food crisis: ABCD of food’ </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:9pt">Thursday 2nd June 2011</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:9pt">http://www.theguardian.com/global-development/poverty-matters/2011/jun/02/abcd-food-giants-dominate-trade 