font-size:10pt"> volatility </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">from Russia</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> and reported record profits for the year</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">. This</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> poses the question on whether the</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">danger of these transnational companies is not their influence over price but th</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">eir approach to food as a commodity </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">which </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">detach</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">es itself from </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">morality </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">of </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">food </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">production. </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> With</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> traders continuing to exert a great deal </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">of influence over the global food system, they should be held accountable to</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> excessive profits from failed harves</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">ts and</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> be</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">come responsible actors.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">The implications of volatility in global food supply </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">and demand for UK food security</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:5pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.34pt; padding-left:4.66pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">As the world experiences increasing volatility </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> food prices, it </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">is easy to </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">understand</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> state</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> rational</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">in exercising</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">isolationism</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">When </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">countries</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> trade level is large enough to in</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">fluence the world market price, then an export ban </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">poses serious</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> ramifications </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">for import led c</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">ountries</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">like </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">the UK</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> When Russia ch</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">ose</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> to close their borders</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">, importer</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> confidence </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">was evidently</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> knocked </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">which</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> caused</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">reactionary</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> stockpiling</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">from</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> importer countries</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">in order to </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">preserve their food </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">security </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">consequentially forcing up</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> the price of grain upwards in what is known as the multiplier effect in export policy.</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> As a consequence the combination of Russian i</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">solationism and the expectation of a late and low yielding British harvest, the UK faced very</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> low grain storages which forced British buyers to look desperately to the EU stockpile </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">which was</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> in no better state. Hence</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> British suppliers were forced to accep</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">t lower quality grain in order to sustain demand</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> forcing </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">British buyers</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> to</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">rely more upon</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> British </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">produce</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> as their main source of input and security.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">However,</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">he E</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">U’s </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">no better with its</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">use of </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">import levies</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-weight:normal">as it </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">use</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> levies</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> to lower</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> tariff</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> in </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">an attempt </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">to protect domestic consumers </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">from</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> higher world market prices.</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> Although they are </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">use</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> fixed tariffs there are still some loopholes</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">contributing </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">world market volatility</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.15pt; padding-left:0.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">With </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">the global g</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">rain market lurching</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> from one crop crisis to another</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">, the demand for food security in the UK is </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">imperative for its survival in achieving the growing demand for quality and affordable food. </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">To keep food affordable, British buyers have relied upon the global market for the answers and the EU has looked to sub</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">sidies. The </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Common Agricultural Policy</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">, in its simplest form is a method of </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">supporting producers and </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">reducing the price of goods for </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">domestic consumers. Even with heavy subsidises on European production, food security questions are being asked in reference to affordability. The burden of economic decline has meant that many people in Britain today are forced to rely upon the good will o</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">f food banks because the cost of living has skyrocketed. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:5pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Whether climate change risks are adequately incorporated in UK food security strategies and planning</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:5pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.15pt; padding-left:0.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">In the words of former Government Scientific Adviser John Beddington, food security creates a </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">“perfect storm” of food shortages, scarce water and insufficient energy resources by 2030.</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">5</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">The prevalence of </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">international </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">environmental security discourse</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> has caused</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> governments </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">to commit to development goals. Depending upon </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">the</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">government’s narrative of </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">environment security</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">, answers the question of whether climate change has been incorporated within food security strategies. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><img src="data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAowAAAACCAYAAADSFo1XAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAAA+SURBVFhH7daxDQBACAMxNs/o/NNSMIEjsYB1BVV/Sdox0IAGNKABDWhAAxrYDcyvaAQIECBAgAABAgROgQcelE8z3iDBtQAAAABJRU5ErkJggg==" width="651" height="1" alt="" style="margin-left:10.35pt; margin-top:7.65pt; position:absolute; z-index:3" /></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:9pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.8pt; padding-left:6.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:9pt">Parliament UK, ‘</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">Agriculture and Food Security’</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:9pt"> http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/research/key-issues-for-the-new-parliament/britain-in-the-world/agriculture-and-food-security/ (accessed 5</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:6pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:9pt"> December 2013)</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.2pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.15pt; padding-left:0.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">In </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">this </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">committee’s recent </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">‘</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">Implementation of the Common Agricultural Policy in Eng</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">land 2014-2020</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">report </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">it identified that the </span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">transfer of subsidies into the</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> Rural Devel</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">opment payment scheme would result in direct subsidies</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> cuts</span><span style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> to British farmers leaving them in a worse state to </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">compete in the marketplace and more </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">open</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> to shocks from poor weather and price vulnerability. ‘In 2012–13 farm incomes fell across </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">most farm types as the effects of unfavourable weather, high input costs and the </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">pound strengthening against the euro, were felt across the cropping and livestock se</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">ctor.’</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">6</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super"> </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.15pt; padding-left:0.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">The UK receives one of the lowest amounts of</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> funding </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">from CAP </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">whereas other European governments </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">view the </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">CAP </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">reform </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">as </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">an </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">implication of more stringent environmental regulations. Living in a farming community myself, </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">the subject of </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">CAP is not talked about with ease as many famers rely upon the payment to balance out their books. British farmers are not inefficient as an industry but the combination </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">increased competition from abroad and the increase in bureaucratic regulation and i</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">nspections, farmers are facing more hours in their offices than on the farm. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.15pt; padding-left:0.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">This is evident in the</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">subsidy shift towards </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">Rural Development </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">which promotes a </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">policy of Greening </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">which includes</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> crop diversification, permanent grasslands and ecological focus</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> areas</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> seems to bypass practicality by tackling sustainability the </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">wrong</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> way round</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">he </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">Greening policy would </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">penalise smaller producers </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">especially, </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">due to </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">their inability to provide sufficient storage for crop diversity </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">comply with grain assurance </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">measures</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> and produce enough to satisfy buyer contracts </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">by filling</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> the standard 30tn lorry load that British grain buyers accept</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">If unpredictable weather conditions are to continue across the UK, </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">smaller producers would be harmed most under the proposals </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">to diversify CAP payments.</span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:normal; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.15pt; padding-left:0.05pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">In a year of exceptionally poor weather the single farm payment is an important element in the keeping the British farming business alive making it imperative that climate security is not perilously placed upon CAP’s shoulders. CAP’s original purpose was t</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">o improve agricultural productivity, so that consumers </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">could </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">have a stable supply of affordable food. Fifty years later, EU Food security at the global level has forced CAP</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> reform</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> to incorporate </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">limate change and sustainable </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">management of natural resource</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">s. However, there has to be a balance. The EU declares that food security is a serious matter that all countries should react to but then use tariffs to protect its members</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">, ostracizing third world producers</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">o maintain sustainable prices for food product</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">ion,</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> the government ha</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> to be cautious </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">not to ‘hijack’</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> the original purpose of CAP</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> too severely</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt"> by environmental policy. </span></li></ol><p style="background-color:#ffffff; font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><img src="data:image/png;base64,iVBORw0KGgoAAAANSUhEUgAAAowAAAACCAYAAADSFo1XAAAAAXNSR0IArs4c6QAAAARnQU1BAACxjwv8YQUAAAAJcEhZcwAADsMAAA7DAcdvqGQAAAA+SURBVFhH7daxDQBACAMxNs/o/NNSMIEjsYB1BVV/Sdox0IAGNKABDWhAAxrYDcyvaAQIECBAgAABAgROgQcelE8z3iDBtQAAAABJRU5ErkJggg==" width="651" height="1" alt="" style="margin-left:9.6pt; margin-top:3.1pt; position:absolute; z-index:2" /></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:9pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.8pt; padding-left:6.2pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:9pt">House of Commons: Environment, Food and Rural Affairs Committee, ‘</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:underline">Implementation of the Common Agricultural Policy in England 2014-2020’ </span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:9pt">Seventh Report of Session 2013–14 http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmselect/cmenvfru/745/745.pdf</span><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:9pt; text-decoration:none"> (accessed on 7th December 2013) </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Gisha; font-size:9pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>